# Dead Gossip — Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
Dead Gossip is a genealogy research web application. Users research, organize and explore family history using AI-assisted document extraction, search and narrative generation.

## Developer Context
The developer is a non-technical Product Manager. She understands systems logically but not syntactically. Follow these rules without exception:
- Explain what you are about to do before you do it, in plain language
- If a change carries risk, say so before making it
- Never make more changes than were asked for
- If completing the request would require touching something outside its stated scope, stop and ask first

## Tech Stack
- **Framework:** Next.js (App Router) with TypeScript (strict mode)
- **UI:** React + Tailwind CSS
- **Database:** PostgreSQL via Supabase (no ORM — raw Supabase query builder)
- **Auth:** Supabase Auth with server-side session checks
- **AI:** Anthropic API (`@anthropic-ai/sdk`)
- **Storage:** Supabase Storage
- **Testing:** Vitest + React Testing Library

## Folder Structure
- `app/` — pages, layouts and API route handlers
- `app/api/` — server-side route handlers only (document processing, story generation, review, merges, places)
- `app/dashboard/` — main authenticated workspace and tree UI
- `app/review/` — review workflows
- `app/person/` — person detail views
- `app/login/` — authentication UI
- `lib/` — shared business logic, Supabase clients, utilities, theming
- `components/` — reusable UI components
- `supabase/` — migrations and SQL schema
- `__tests__/` — Vitest test files

## Coding Conventions
- Use App Router conventions — no Pages Router patterns
- API endpoints live in `app/api/**/route.ts` with named exports (`GET`, `POST`, `DELETE`)
- Use `"use client"` and `"use server"` directives explicitly and correctly
- Import paths use the `@/*` alias — never use relative paths like `../../`
- Filenames are kebab-case, folders are domain-grouped
- Always check auth and filter by `user_id` before any data operation

## Environment Variables
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL` — public, safe for client
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY` — public, safe for client
- `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` — server-side only, never expose to client or log

## Hard Rules

### Database safety
- Never modify `schema.sql` or create a new migration file without explicitly stating you are doing so and why
- Never combine a schema change with a feature change in the same session — do them separately
- Never delete or rename a column without flagging it — existing data will be affected
- If a query touches a table that already has data, say so before running it

### API key safety
- `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` must only appear in server-side files (`app/api/`, server actions, `lib/` utilities called from server)
- Never reference it in a `"use client"` file or pass it through a client-accessible route

### Scope discipline
- Only change what was asked — do not refactor, rename or reorganize adjacent code unless explicitly asked
- If fixing a bug requires changing something outside the immediate file, ask first
- Do not add new dependencies without flagging it and explaining why it is needed

### Before any large change
- Remind the developer to commit current working state before proceeding
- If a change touches more than two files, summarize what will be affected before starting

## AI Features
- Anthropic API calls live in `app/api/process-document/route.ts` and `app/api/regenerate-story/route.ts`
- Keep AI calls server-side only
- Always handle API errors gracefully — a failed AI call should never crash the UI or leave data in a broken state
- When extracting data from documents, confidence level should travel with the extracted value

## Domain Context
- Users work with historical documents: census records, land deeds, court records, vital records, probate files, tax assessments, church registers
- Names, dates and places are often ambiguous, misspelled or in archaic formats
- Source citation and evidence confidence matter — treat uncertain data differently from confirmed data
- Users often work across multiple family lines and need to connect people, places and events over time

## End of Session
After any significant agent session, briefly summarize:
- What was changed
- What files were touched
- Whether any database changes were made
- Any known loose ends or follow-up needed
